package wasmcloud:postgres@0.2.0;

/// Interface for querying a Postgres database.
///
/// Unlike `wasmcloud:postgres@0.1.1-draft`, every operation is an `async func`,
/// so a single component can issue many in-flight queries concurrently without
/// the `wasi:io/poll` ceremony required under wasip2. `query` also streams its
/// result rows rather than buffering the whole result set in host memory before
/// returning.
interface query {
  use types.{pg-value, column-name, row, error};

  /// Query a Postgres database, leaving connection/session management to the
  /// callee/implementer of this interface (normally a provider configured with
  /// connection credentials).
  ///
  /// Queries *must* be parameterized, with named arguments in the form of
  /// `$<integer>`, for example:
  ///
  /// ```
  /// SELECT email,username FROM users WHERE uuid=$1;
  /// ```
  ///
  /// On success the result is delivered in three parts:
  ///
  /// 1. `list<column-name>` — the result columns, in order, delivered once up
  ///    front. Position `i` names the value at position `i` of every `row`.
  /// 2. `stream<row>` — the result rows, produced incrementally as the database
  ///    returns them. The caller owns the stream and drives it to completion (or
  ///    drops it early to stop consuming).
  /// 3. `future<result<_, error>>` — a completion signal that resolves once the
  ///    row stream is exhausted. It reports an error encountered *after* the
  ///    column header was sent (e.g. a failure partway through a large result),
  ///    which the row stream itself has no way to surface.
  ///
  /// The outer `result` reports failures that occur before any rows stream, such
  /// as a rejected statement or a lost connection.
  query: async func(query: string, params: list<pg-value>)
    -> result<tuple<list<column-name>, stream<row>, future<result<_, error>>>, error>;

  /// Perform a batch query (which could contain multiple statements) against a
  /// Postgres database, leaving connection/session management to the
  /// callee/implementer of this interface (normally a provider configured with
  /// connection credentials).
  ///
  /// No user-provided or untrusted data should be used with this query --
  /// parameters are not allowed.
  ///
  /// This query *can* be used to execute multi-statement queries (common in
  /// migrations).
  query-batch: async func(query: string) -> result<_, error>;
}
